PMID: 10468394 [Indexed for MEDLINE]


691. Soc Sci Med. 1999 Oct;49(7):967-79. doi: 10.1016/s0277-9536(99)00193-8.

Subjective life expectancy in the US: correspondence to actuarial estimates by 
age, sex and race.

Mirowsky J(1).

Author information:
(1)Department of Sociology, Ohio State University, Columbus 43210-1353, USA. 
mirowsky.1@osu.edu

This study maps the relationship between subjective and actuarial life 
expectancy in a 1995 national sample of 2037 Americans of ages 18-95. Subjective 
estimates parallel age-specific actuarial ones based on current age-specific 
mortality rates. However males expect to live about 3 years longer than the 
actuarial estimate and blacks expect to live about 6 years longer. The apparent 
optimism remains after adjusting for socioeconomic status and the signs and 
symptoms of good health. Contrary to economists' rational-expectations 
hypothesis, young adults do not adjust their life expectancies upward to account 
